'''ASSITEJ''', the '''International Association of Theatre for Children and Young People''', ({{lang-fr|'''Association Internationale du Théâtre de l’Enfance et la Jeunesse'''}}) was established in 1965 as an international alliance of professionals involved in [[Theatre for Early Years|theatre for children]] and young people. There are 83 national centres globally.<ref>{{Cite web | title = ASSITEJ International (Association International du Theatre pour l´Enfance et la Jeunesse) | accessdate = 2010-09-09 | url = http://www.assitej-international.org/english/home.aspx | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101011102857/http://www.assitej-international.org/english/home.aspx| archivedate= 11 October 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> The President of ASSITEJ is Yvette Hardie.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The executive committee {{!}} Assitej International|url = http://www.assitej-international.org/en/the-executive-committee/|website = www.assitej-international.org|accessdate = 2015-12-07}}</ref>
ASSITEJ facilitates worldwide access and the exchange of ideas and cultural traditions for professionals involved in [[Theatre for Early Years|theatre for children]] and young people.
The ASSITEJ World Congresses<ref>{{Cite web |title = History of the event :: ASSITEJ 2008 |accessdate = 2008-10-05 |url = http://www.assitej.com.au/about-us/history-of-the-event |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080724224920/http://www.assitej.com.au/about-us/history-of-the-event |archive-date = 2008-07-24 |dead-url = yes |df = }}</ref> have been held in [[Warsaw]], [[Prague]], [[Lyon]], [[Madrid]], [[Adelaide]],<ref>[http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?docID=news861210_0007_4525 Jeremy Eccles, (10 December 1986), Young Actors Prepare To Stage The Future, ''Sydney Morning Herald'', Sydney, p. 16]</ref> [[Seoul]], [[Rostov on Don]], [[Tromsø]], [[Albany, New York|Albany]], etc.<ref>{{Cite web | title = 17th ASSITEJ World Congress 2011 | accessdate = 2010-09-09 | url = http://www.assitej2011.info/?lang=3 }}</ref>
ASSITEJ is affiliated with several practitioner networks, including the International Inclusive Arts Network (IIAN)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://inclusiveartsnetwork.com/about/ |title=IIAN website |access-date=2014-07-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320052604/http://inclusiveartsnetwork.com/about/ |archive-date=2017-03-20 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> and the International Theatre for Young Audiences Research Network (ITYARN).<ref>[http://www.ityarn.org/ ITYARN website]</ref>
