'''Gary Braasch''' (1944 – March 7, 2016) was an environmental photographer and writer for nature and [[biodiversity]] across the globe. Braasch was born in Omaha, Nebraska and made his home in [[Oregon]].
==Life==
{{Empty section|date=November 2015}}
==Work== '''Gary Braasch''' has been photographing for over 40 years and has been published by [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']], ''[[LIFE]]'', ''[[New York Times Magazine]]'', [[Discover (magazine)|''Discover'']], and many more. Braasch has also won the 2006 [[Ansel Adams Award for Conservation Photography|Ansel Adams Award]] from the [[Sierra Club]] and the Outstanding Nature Photographer citation from the North American Nature Photography Association.<ref name=Official>{{cite web|url=http://www.braaschphotography.com/|website=Gary Braasch Environmental Photography|accessdate=28 October 2015}}</ref> He died at the age of 72 while snorkeling at the [[Great Barrier Reef]] on March 7, 2016.<ref>http://malaysiandigest.com/frontpage/29-4-tile/598825-u-s-climate-change-campaigner-dies-snorkelling-at-great-barrier-reef.html</ref><ref>http://dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2016/03/08/too-soon-gone-gargiygguygy-braasch-visual-chronicler-of-climate-change/?_r=0{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
===Publication=== '''Gary Braasch's''' work has been published many times involving environmental awareness across several magazines and publishers.
*Antarctic Seabird Research (International Wildlife) *Great Smoky Mountains National Park Biodiversity ([[Audubon (magazine)|Audubon]]) *The Threat of Oil Drilling in Alaska's Arctic ([[BBC Wildlife]]) *Tropical Forest Studies in Peru ([[The Nature Conservancy]]) *Anaconda Research in Venezuela ([[Smithsonian]]) *Honeybees and Native Pollinators ([[Natural History]]) *Endangered Wood Stork Nesting in the Everglades ([[Audubon (magazine)|Audubon]]) *Rare Plant Rescue in Hawaii (Smithsonian and Discover) *Climate Change in Florida and Alaska ([[Natural Resources Defense Council]])
