{{Infobox Artwork | image_file = Jean Léon Gerome 1896 La Vérité sortant du puits.JPG | title = Truth coming out of her well | artist = [[Jean-Léon Gérôme]] | year = 1896 | medium = [[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_metric = 91 | width_metric = 72 | height_imperial = | width_imperial = | metric_unit = cm | imperial_unit = | city = [[Moulins, Allier]] | museum = Musée Anne de Beaujeu }} '''''La Vérité sortant du puits armée de son martinet pour châtier l'humanité''''' (English: '''''Truth coming from the well armed with her whip to chastise mankind''''') is an 1896 painting by the French artist [[Jean-Léon Gérôme]].
==Overview== In 1895, Gérôme had painted a similar work, ''Mendacibus et histrionibus occisa in puteo jacet alma Veritas'' (English: ''The nurturer Truth lies in a well, having been killed by liars and actors'').<ref>{{cite book|title=The Academy|date=11 May 1895|publisher=J. Murray|pages=409|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8F08AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA409|language=en}}</ref> It has been suggested that both paintings (like a similar, later work by [[Édouard Debat-Ponsan]]) were a comment on the [[Dreyfus affair]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pouillon|first1=François|title=Dictionnaire des orientalistes de langue française|date=2012|publisher=KARTHALA Editions|isbn=9782811107901|page=466|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UVPhEUNg7CcC&pg=PA466|language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Brauer|first1=Fae|title=Rivals and Conspirators: The Paris Salons and the Modern Art Centre|date=2013|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|location=Newcastle upon Tyne|isbn=9781443863704|pages=205-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jWBJDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA205|language=en}}</ref> It has also been suggested that the painting is an expression of Gérôme's hostility towards the [[Impressionist]] movement, to which he was violently opposed.<ref name="mab" /> However, in a preface that Gérôme wrote for [[Émile Bayard]]'s ''Le Nu Esthétique'', he refers to the influence photography had had upon painting: {{Verse translation|lang=fr | La photographie est un art. La photographie force les artistes à se dépouiller de la vieille routine et à oublier les vieilles formules. Elle nous a ouvert les yeux et forcé à regarder ce qu'auparavant nous n'avions jamais vu, service considérable et inappréciable qu'elle a rendu à l'Art. C'est grâce à elle que la vérité est enfin sortie de son puits. Elle n'y rentrera plus.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bibliothèque nationale (France)|title=Autour de Turandot|date=1997|publisher=Bibliothèque nationale de France|pages=33|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OW5TAAAAMAAJ|language=fr}}</ref> | Photography is an art. It forces artists to discard their old routine and forget their old formulas. It has opened our eyes and forced us to see that which previously we have not seen; a great and inexpressible service for Art. It is thanks to photography that Truth has finally come out of her well. She will never go back.}}
The expression refers to a widespread translation of an aphorism of the philosopher [[Democritus]], "Of truth we know nothing, for truth is in a well [lit. in an abyss]."<ref>{{cite book|last1=Diogenes Laertius|title=Lives of Eminent Philosophers|publisher= IX, 72. Perseus Project, Tufts University|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:abo:tlg,0004,001:9:11}}</ref> The nudity of the model refers to the expression 'the naked truth'.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Noël|first1=Benoît|last2=Hournon|first2=Jean|title=Parisiana: la capitale des peintres au XIXème siècle|date=2006|publisher=DISLAB|location=Paris|isbn=9782952721400|pages=147|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j63bUC2bjnoC&pg=PA147|language=fr}}</ref> According to his biographer [[Charles Moreau-Vauthier]], Gérôme slept with the painting above his bed and was found after his death with his arm stretched out towards it in a gesture of farewell.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Moreau-Vauthier|first1=Charles|last2=Gérôme|first2=Jean Léon|title=Gérôme: peintre et sculpteur|date=1906|publisher=Hachette|page=6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YTlGAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA6|language=fr}}</ref>
[[Image:Truth Leaving the Well.gif|thumb|left|In ''Nec Mergitur'' (Latin: ''Nor is she submerged'') or ''La Vérité sortant du puits'' (1898) by [[Édouard Debat-Ponsan]], clerical reaction is attempting to pull Truth back into the well]]The painting was exhibited at the [[Salon (Paris)|Salon]] in 1896.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Ackerman|first=Gerald M.|year=1986|title=The life and work of Jean-Léon Gérôme: with a catalogue raisonné|publisher=[[Sotheby's]]|p=276|isbn=9780856673115}}</ref> Since 1978 it has been part of the permanent exhibition at the [[:fr:Musée Anne-de-Beaujeu|Musée Anne de Beaujeu]] in [[Moulins, Allier|Moulins]], France.<ref name=mab>http://www.mab.allier.fr/2045-les-collections-permanentes.htm</ref>
